args:
Cassandra's plan is to protect the merchant
who has been cut off by the Imperial Army.
If the group can get him to town, the lantern
festival can proceed. But by the time they track
down the man, he has already been beset by
imperials. What could their reasons be...?
Phew! This forest is bigger than\nI expected. I was hoping to have this\nlittle jaunt all wrapped up already.
But I think we're finally near the highway,\nso put some hustle in your bustle, Curran!
All I wanted from today was to attend\na festival. Instead I'm doing...THIS.
...You want to go protect the merchant\nwho's been cut off on the highway?
Yes. He's up there on the highway\nsomewhere, but he'll never make it\ninto town with the blockade.

We don't know the extent of the Empire's
reach, but they're not likely to let that
man simply walk away whistling if they
happen to come across him.
Yeah, true. One poor merchant ain't gonna\nbe no match for a buncha imperials.
Exactly. So I propose we cut through the\nforest to the highway, find the merchant,\nand lead him back to town the same way.

We'll save the poor man from an imperial
lashing—and if we get the festival goods
delivered along the way, it's stoning
two birds with a single rock.
That sounds like a decent plan to me.
Right then! You two strapping young chaps\ncan leave escorting the merchant to us.
I take it I don't qualify as a ＂strapping\nyoung chap＂ and will instead be dragged\nabout according to your random whims?
That little frown of yours makes me worry\nyou are most dissatisfied, Curran.
I certainly don't know you well enough\nto presume familiarity, but...
Well, you just seem very passionate\nabout all of this.
About the festival, I mean. Do you have\nsome special attachment to it, maybe?
You seem very upset at the thought\nof its being interrupted.
Do I? Well, isn't that a wonder!\nBut no, there's no special reason.
You're not much for lying,\nare you, my lady?

You seem like the type who plans their
steps carefully, yet here you are throwing
caution to the wind for some small-town
festival. I just wonder why.
How very rude of you to imply I don't\nnormally help those in trouble.
Especially after I just loaned you a great\nsum of money back in town.
Perhaps your position as an inquisitor\njust makes you naturally suspicious.

Guilty as charged, I suppose. When I get
curious about something, I can't help but
ask questions—it's something of an
occupational hazard.
I made a horse's rear of myself trying\nto get a woman to spill her secrets,\nand for that I apologize, my lady.
Oh, posh. You've nothing to apologize\nfor. I WOULD, however, prefer you give\nthat ＂my lady＂ bit a rest.
I may look a stunner, but I've been around\nmore than twice as many years as you.\nMagic just keeps me young and fresh.
Yes, I'm aware of that. But there's more\nto being a lady than mere age, agreed?
Goodness, you do like to play it cool.\nWell, we ought to be free of this forest\nsoon, so let's hurry to the highway and—
Oy! You there! Gimme all yer goods!
*pant* *pant* B-but these items are\non their way to my customers!
Oh dear. I do hate how right\nI am sometimes.
Damn imperials are faster than I thought.\n...HEY! You all right, friend?!
We hail from Quinbell. Are you the\nmerchant carrying goods for the festival?
Yeah, I've got tools and supplies for\nthe stalls, plus a whole pile of candles\nfor the lanterns.
Well, we certainly can't allow all such\ngoodies to be stolen by these ruffians.\nNow be a dear and get behind us.
I gots no idea who you folks are,\nbut if ya don't wanna get smacked,\nhand over that there merchant fella!

Oh, I most resolutely refuse. You, sir,
are little more than a common bandit,
and I'll not let you take advantage of
this poor and honest working man.
Right then! Looks like somebody\nwants a beatin'!
Guess we're done talking here.\nYou ready for this?

No former court sorceress worth her salt
is ever NOT ready. And honestly, I'm a bit
tickled at the thought of engaging in a
scrap in this lovely getup.

Say, do you notice anything...strange
about these imperials? Their weapons
are in terrible condition, and they don't
seem very comfortable handling them.
Looks like they might be soldiers\ndefending the nearby border fort.
Yes, perhaps. But what would bring such\nindividuals to a place like this? ...Hmm?
Uh oh. That looks like an entire regiment\nof the Imperial Army!
Are you the people who attacked my\nsubordinates? ...Well? Out with it!

Why, heavens no! We're just a pair of
travelers in a VERY nice set of clothes.
But never mind that, dearie—I take it
you're the commanding officer here?
In that case, I'd like to know why your\npeople are crossing the border in order\nto harass this poor, innocent merchant?
There's a festival being held in the town\ndown the road, and it would be very poor\nform for you to disrupt such a grand event.
Down the road? A festival?\nHa ha ha!
Ah, but that is rich. I'll have to make\nsure to tell my superiors that one.
Surely a pair like you can come up with\na better excuse than a ＂festival＂?
Don't play dumb! I sussed out who you are\nthe moment you came all the way out here\nto protect that merchant.
You likely hoped to wear unusual clothes\nto conceal your identities, but you're\nclearly soldiers of New Alberia.
Heh. Surprised? The Empire isn't so\ndense as all that, it seems.
There's no festival in that town—it's just\nan excuse to smuggle military supplies\nto the resistance!
What the hell are you talking about?!
